			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">[Note:  A detailed history of this document, complete with changes to the system during it's evolution can be found <a href="http://www.scienceofwar.net/forum/viewtopic.php?p=20636#20636" target="_blank" class="postlink">here</a>]
<br />

<br />
<b>Summary</b>: 
<br />

<br />
Loot is just one of many rewards that come with being in Science of War, but it's something that's often a source of controversy in many guilds. We hope that clear rules and guidelines will set the proper expectations about the rewards you can expect to reap as you fight with us.
<br />

<br />
Some loot is dispensed the moment it drops, and some loot is banked for future use. But before we get into each of those two areas, our general principles governing loot decisions can be summed up like so: We want a long-lasting guild with low turnover. We therefore value loyalty to and time spent with the guild. Because we value these things, out loot system will reward loyal, long-term membership.
<br />

<br />
Science of War handles loot via an auction system. Guild members earn points via a variety of activities and can spend those points in an auction whenever loot drops. An auction system is the best tool for determining how much someone wants or needs an item over the long run because it forces us to choose what we'll purchase with our scarce points. This system encourages members to evaluate equipment choice and to consider long-term upgrade paths. The end result is more loot in the right hands. 
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">How are raid points calculated?</span>
<br />

<br />
- Points are awarded based on what we accomplish during the raid and apportioned by time. If we kill 10 points worth of beasties and you are there for 50% of the raid duration, you'll earn 5 points. 
<br />

<br />
- Calendared mobs are worth (2 * per tier level). (Example: Cazic Thule is a tier 5 calendared mob. He's therefore worth ten points.) However, for a raid participant to earn all four points associated with killing Cazic Thule, they'd have to be present for the entire raid, not just log in and get a CoH right before we engage the mob.
<br />

<br />
- Plane clearings are worth one point per hour. Most clearing-drudgery and exploratory raids will earn points by the hour. Most other encounters will earn points per raid-level named kill.
<br />

<br />
- The first time we kill any named, raid-level mob, each person on the kill will earn an extra point.
<br />

<br />
- If we FAIL to kill our target, but do give it our best shot, then each raid attendee is awarded one point.
<br />

<br />
- If a raid starts on time (give or take 5 minutes), that is worth an additional point for all of the people that are ON TIME. Starting means that raid members are grouped, buffed, and the first pull or move order is given within five minutes of the published start-time.
<br />

<br />
- Three different encounters in a single evening is a 'hat trick' and earns every attendee a bonus of three points. You must attend all three encounters to earn this hat-trick bonus.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">So, what does it take for a raid to qualify for DKP?</span>
<br />

<br />
<ul>
<br />
<li>A raid must consist of 12 or more people flying the SoW guild tag.
<br />
<li>The target must be a <a href="http://www.scienceofwar.net:8887/listEncounters.jsp">listed encounter</a>
<br />
<li>An officer must OK the raid, must be present for the entire raid, and must either oversee (or delegate) loot distribution
<br />
<li>A well documented Post-Mortem must be written, including by-the-hour attendance
<br />
<li>A spoils of war post must be made. 
<br />
</ul>
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">What if I don't get included in a raid when I KNOW I was there?  How do I get my DKP for it?</span>
<br />

<br />
Actually, it's quite simple.
<br />

<br />
The DKP Administrator can ONLY assign points based on the attendance list in the post-mortem.  Even if they know, beyond a shadow of a doubt, that another person attended, they are only allowed to assign points based on that P-M.
<br />

<br />
If you weren't given credit for being on a raid, you need to speak with the raidleader and have that person edit their attendance list, adding your participation in a post in the thread stating the person was added, and how many points they recieve.  Example:
<br />

<br />
Added attendance:  Leatherneck +3 points
<br />

<br />

<br />
Raid leader PM's the me, alerting me to the change and it'll get fixed.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">When does my bid take effect?</span>
<br />

<br />
You can only bid with the points in <a href="http://www.scienceofwar.net:8887/listPlayers.jsp">your account</a> at the time of the bid. (If the points aren't posted on the website, you DON'T have them yet.) You can't bank on having extra points because of the raid you are on.  IF you go in the hole on a bid you make, you still incur the penalty even if the raid you are on would cover it.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">How do I get points?</span>
<br />

<br />
At this point in time, there are 4 ways to earn points:
<br />

<br />
1)  You get the total of your <a href="http://www.scienceofwar.net/review.htm" target="_blank" class="postlink">review</a> (multiplied by your 60-day raid percentage) on your anniversary date or as soon as possible thereafter.
<br />
2)  You get raid points at the time the raid is posted in the post-mortem
<br />
3)  You get sellback points at the time a guildmember pays for your gear
<br />
4)  The guild leadership may decide to provide incentives along the way and as those incentives are posted awarded, you'll recieve the points
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">So...if I go in the hole, then what?</span>
<br />

<br />
You may not bid yourself into a hole. If the lootmaster knows that you'll be in the hole with a bid, your bid will not be allowed. However, accidents can happen and if they do, you are penalized. You are penalized for twice the amount of the overdraft and then we take off an additional 10 points. As long as you have a negative balance, you will not be able to bid on another item.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">What if I wasn't charged correctly for an item I bought?</span>
<br />

<br />
Mea Culpa.
<br />

<br />
Only two things could have happened.  It was either:
<br />

<br />
a) entered into the spoils of war post incorrectly or 
<br />
b) entered into the database incorrectly.
<br />

<br />
If it's entered into the spoils of war post incorrectly, the lootmeister for that raid needs to edit their post and PM the points admin alerting me to the change.
<br />

<br />
If it's entered into the database incorrectly, PM the points administrator.
<br />

<br />
In either case, you will not see the actual value of your purchase change.  Instead, you will recieve a bump in points based on the amount of the difference.  It will appear as an adjustment.  This is because I am unable to change the amount of a purchase on a raid without deleting the whole raid and starting over.
<br />

<br />
Example of operations:
<br />

<br />

<br />
Vova has 250 points
<br />
Vova buys a Chastity Belt for 50 DKP
<br />
An error, either on the spoils of war post or because the points admin is a bonehead, enters the DKP cost at 150.
<br />

<br />
This leaves Vova with 100 points.
<br />

<br />
The error gets corrected.
<br />

<br />
An adjustment is given for 100 points.
<br />

<br />
This will show as:
<br />

<br />
Vova has 350 points (the original 250 + the 100 adjustment)
<br />
Vova buys a Chastity Belt for 150 points.
<br />
Vova has 200 points.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">What are these points good for?</span>
<br />

<br />
Equipment purchases, which fall into two categories.
<br />

<br />
1.  Equipment Purchases: When equipment, spells, and keys drop, members who can and will use those items may bid on them by moving to a special auction channel. The raid's lootmaster will announce TWICE in the raid channel that an auction is underway in the auction channel and he will link the item in each of these announcements. The format for the announcements in the general channel is: 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">"DROP: Item Name All who can and will use this item [with the exception of EXCEPTION LIST] please /join sowpoints and submit your bid now."</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> 
<br />
 
<br />
Only one item will be active at once in the auction channel and bidding will proceed as follows: 
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Lootmaster tells auction: "Taking bids on ItemX - Please send your bid to the channel if you can and will use it." 
<br />

<br />
Bidder01 tells sowpoints: "I bid 20" 
<br />
Bidder02 tells sowpoints: "I bid 30" 
<br />

<br />
(no activitity for a minute" 
<br />

<br />
Lootmaster tells sowpoints: "The high bid on itemx is 30. Going once." 
<br />
Lootmaster tells sowpoints: "The high bid on itemx is 30. Going twice." 
<br />
Lootmaster tells sowpoints: "The high bid on itemx is 30. Sold to Bidder02 at a cost of 30 points." </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> 
<br />

<br />
2.  Bank Withdrawals: Members may spend points on items in the guild bank. Point values on bank items are set at the banker's discretion.
<br />

<br />
Another way to use your points is buying quests.  Though the guild is committed to helping every member achieve his class and racial epic, members may also purchase multi-group raids for non-epic quests such as the 10th Ring War or 8th Coldain Prayer Shawl. Quests cost one point per raid participant per hour and members are responsible for leading the raid from beginning to end or for finding a substitute raid leader. 
<br />

<br />
The player who buys a raid guarantees himself loot rights for the ONE item on that raid.  All other items are bid upon per usual SoW rules.  The quest buyer is granted those points up to, but not in excess of, the amount paid for the raid (one point per raid participant per hour).
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">What if there is a tie?</span>
<br />

<br />
There are no ties.  First person to set a bid has that bid. You may never bid the same as someone else. Either beat the high bid or not.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">What about guests?</span>
<br />

<br />
A guest who is REQUIRED for a raid to happen will be given temporary points equal to the total expected points for the raid in negotation with the raid leader. (For instance, if a raid is going to award members four points for a raid, then the guest would receive four points at the beginning of the raid for use in bidding.) 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Ok, what about non-required guests?</span>
<br />

<br />
If they're not required, they won't be eligible for the temporary points.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">What about applicants?</span>
<br />

<br />
Applicants have some special rules.  An applicant to the guild earns points for raids attended. Applicants may bid zero on any item.  This will save some items from rot.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">What about stuff that's going to rot?</span>
<br />

<br />
Not much rots when the minimum bid needed to save any item from rot is zero points.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">I play more than one character.  What about me?</span>
<br />

<br />
Alts don't earn points ever. If we FORCE you to play an alt for a raid, then you may use your main's account to bid on items. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">No, I mean I play them at the same time.</span>
<br />

<br />
Oh, well in that case, you may only obtain items after all regular members have been able to bid on them.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">So, how does this sellback thing work?</span>
<br />

<br />
We encourage guild members to recycle equipment (not cash). A member that no longer needs a piece of droppable gear (not cash) may GIVE that item to the lootmaster for auction at the current raid. Once an item is given to the lootmaster, the lootmaster will hold an auction for that item. If someone wins the item, the points are deducted from the winner's account and credited to the recycler's account after being multiplied by the recycler's 60-day raid attendance percentage. If nobody wants it, the lootmaster gives the item back. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Hey, I paid good money for this item.  When I put it up for a Player-to-Player auction I want to make sure it's worth it.  Can I put a reserve on this?</span>
<br />

<br />
Absolutely.  You are free to put in a reserve on any item you place up for auction.  Make sure the Auctioneer knows before bidding begins that you have a reserve.  And make sure they announce that reserve in the points channel before bidding begins.
<br />

<br />
Example:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Player-to-Player Auction:  Lodizal Shell Shield.  There is a reserve of 10 DKP on this item.  Please join sowpoints:kkthxu~ and start bidding.  This is a CAWU auction, first of two calls.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Ok, I go linkdead/AFK sometimes.  What if I miss an auction because of that?</span>
<br />

<br />
All auctions will be handled in a timely manner.  If you are unable to be present during an auction, there's not much we can do about that.  We won't hold up an auction for one person, not even if that person is you.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">I don't type so godo.  Waht about em?</span>
<br />

<br />
If you send in a bid that's an OBVIOUS typo, you have until the loot master calls "sold" to correct your bid. You are reponsible owning your bid once winner is declared.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">I misread the stats on an item. I don't want it but I've already started bidding on it. Can I withdraw from the auction?</span>
<br />

<br />
Yes, but the auction will have to start over and you will be penalized for wasting the raid's time. You'll be charged 10% of your DKP balance at the time of your withdrawal if you withdraw from an auction in this manner.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">How can I find out how many points I have, as well as everyone else?</span>
<br />

<br />
A <a href="http://www.scienceofwar.net:8887/dkppro.jsp" target="_blank" class="postlink">publicly-viewable points tracking system</a> will show current member points totals and a transaction log for each member. This system will also track lifetime points earned and other statistics.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Are we actually paying our points to other members for their participation when we buy a quest raid?</span>
<br />

<br />
Not directly, but this is, in effect, what will happen. 
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Does attendance at the quest event count toward our overall points?</span>
<br />

<br />
All guild raids will be worth at least a single point. Most raids will be worth more. All epic queue items are a guild obligation and are a pure benefit of reaching member2. No guild member will be charged for any queue-eligible epic quest.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Can I win more than once in an evening?</span>
<br />

<br />
Though you may win more than once per evening if you've got the points to win more than once, you should remember that others also need upgrades and that monopolization of drops doesn't win you any friends. Try to find a balance.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Can I talk to my friends first and see what they're going to bid?  I really want this item, and don't want to pay alot for it if I don't have to.</span>
<br />

<br />
You may not contrive to fix bids behind the scenes. You shouldn't talk to others about what they're bidding, you shouldn't try to discourage them from bidding, and so on. Don't ask, don't tell when it comes to your bidding.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Leatherneck, you're so cool, and this has helped me so much.  Can I buy you a piece of gear in auction?  How about from the guildbank?</span>
<br />

<br />
All bids are on a can-and-will-use basis. You may not purchase items for alts or friends.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">What if nobody bids against me?</span>
<br />

<br />
You pay however many points you bid, whether that number is zero or 300.
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-weight: bold">Why not make uncontested bids free/one point?</span>
<br />

<br />
Say you have a member who has a much higher amount of points than anyone else?  They can continuously bid their bank, and if nobody is able to bid more, they'd get the item for free/one point. That's just not fair to everyone else.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
